// Role: Senior Angular Developer & Google Style Guide Enforcement
// Goal: Maintain a world-class, scalable, and readable codebase following Google's Angular & TypeScript Style Guides.

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 0. GOOGLE STYLE GUIDE PRINCIPLES (STRICT ENFORCEMENT)
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Apply the 'Rule of One': One component, directive, or service per file.
// Apply 'LIFT':
// - Locate code quickly (intuitive structure).
// - Identify code at a glance (file name = class name).
// - Flat structure (max 7 files per folder usually).
// - Try to be DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself).

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1. TECHNOLOGY STACK & CORE PRINCIPLES
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// - Framework: Angular 18+ (Standalone Components REQUIRED)
// - Styling: Tailwind CSS v3.4+ (Utility-first)
// - UI Library: PrimeNG (for complex data components only)
// - State Management: Angular Signals (Primary), RxJS (Intermediate)
// - Language: TypeScript 5+ (Strict Mode)

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 2. NAMING CONVENTIONS (Google TS Style)
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// - Classes: PascalCase (e.g., `HeroDetailComponent`)
// - Files: kebab-case (e.g., `hero-detail.component.ts`)
// - Methods/Variables: camelCase (e.g., `getHero`, `heroList`)
// - Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (for global/static), camelCase (for local immutable).
// - Interfaces: PascalCase, DO NOT use 'I' prefix (e.g., `User` not `IUser`).
// - Observables: Append `$` suffix (e.g., `hero$`).
// - Signals: No suffix needed, or context-specific (e.g., `userSignal` if ambiguous).

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 3. CODING STANDARDS & MEMBER ORDERING
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Order of Class Members:
// 1. Properties (public -> protected -> private)
// 2. ViewChildren / Inputs / Outputs
// 3. Constructor
// 4. Lifecycle Hooks (ngOnInit, ngOnDestroy...)
// 5. Public Methods
// 6. Private Methods

// Structure:
// - Small Functions: Limit functions to ~20 lines where possible.
// - Immutability: Prefer `readonly` property modifiers and `const` for variables.
// - Strict Typing: NO `any`. Explicit return types for public methods.

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 4. STYLING GUIDELINES (Tailwind First)
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// - Primary: Use Tailwind utility classes for EVERYTHING possible.
// - Secondary: Use Semantic Tokens (`text-primary-500`, `bg-glass-panel`).
// - Restricted: SCSS only for complex `@keyframes` or legacy overrides.
// - Glassmorphism: Use `<app-glass-card>` and shared components.

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 5. ANGULAR ARCHITECTURE
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// - Components: `standalone: true`, `ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush`.
// - Dependency Injection: Use `inject()` instead of constructor usage.
// - State: Use `signal()`, `computed()`, `effect()` for local state.
// - Forms: ReactiveForms with Typed interfaces (`FormControl<string>`).

// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 6. MIGRATION RULES
// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
// When touching legacy code:
// 1. Rename files to kebab-case if needed (should be done).
// 2. Convert `constructor` DI to `inject()`.
// 3. Convert local state to Signals.
// 4. Ensure `standalone: true`.
// 5. Replace custom SCSS with Tailwind utilities.
